# GitHub Pages Deploy – Static HTML App

## Prerequisites (already installed on this machine)

- **Git** `2.45.1` – configured as `Jakub Lada <Jakub.Lada@direct.cz>`
- **GitHub CLI** `gh 2.87.3` – authenticated as **Alcarno** via `gh auth login --web`
- **Python** with `qrcode[pil]` package – for generating QR codes

## PowerShell notes

This machine runs **PowerShell** (not bash). Key differences:
- Use `;` instead of `&&` to chain commands
- HEREDOC (`<<'EOF'`) does NOT work – pass commit messages as simple strings
- Refresh PATH after installing tools: `$env:Path = [System.Environment]::GetEnvironmentVariable("Path","Machine") + ";" + [System.Environment]::GetEnvironmentVariable("Path","User")`

## Deploy steps

### 1. Prepare the project
- Main HTML file MUST be named `index.html` (GitHub Pages serves it by default)
- Rename if needed: `Rename-Item "old-name.html" "index.html"`

### 2. Initialize Git and commit
```powershell
git init
git add -A
git commit -m "Initial commit: <short description>"
```

### 3. Create public GitHub repo and push
```powershell
gh repo create <repo-name> --public --source=. --remote=origin --push
```

### 4. Enable GitHub Pages (legacy deploy from branch)
```powershell
gh api repos/Alcarno/<repo-name>/pages -X POST -f "build_type=workflow" -f "source[branch]=master" -f "source[path]=/"
gh api repos/Alcarno/<repo-name>/pages -X PUT -f "build_type=legacy" -f "source[branch]=master" -f "source[path]=/"
```

### 5. Trigger first build manually (often needed)
```powershell
gh api repos/Alcarno/<repo-name>/pages/builds -X POST
```

### 6. Verify build status
```powershell
gh api repos/Alcarno/<repo-name>/pages/builds/latest
```
Wait until `"status":"built"` appears. Usually takes 30-60 seconds.

### 7. Live URL
```
https://alcarno.github.io/<repo-name>/
```

## Subsequent updates
```powershell
git add -A
git commit -m "<message>"
git push origin master
```
GitHub Pages rebuilds automatically on push. Takes ~1-2 minutes.

## Rename repository (changes URL)
```powershell
gh repo rename <new-name> --yes
git remote set-url origin https://github.com/Alcarno/<new-name>.git
```
Old URL auto-redirects to new one.

## Generate QR code for the page
```powershell
python -c "import qrcode; img = qrcode.make('https://alcarno.github.io/<repo-name>/'); img.save('qr-code.png')"
```
